description: From Middle English fremde, fremede (“strange, foreign”), from Old English fremde, fremede, fremeþe (“foreign, strange”), from Proto-Germanic *framaþiz (“foreign, not one's own”). Cognate with Scots fremmit, frempt (“fremd”), West Frisian frjemd (“strange, fremd”), Dutch vreemd (“strange, foreign”), German fremd (“fremd, strange, foreign”), Swedish främmande (“foreign, outlandish, strange”). More at from.

adjectives.description: fremd (comparative fremder or more fremd, superlative fremdest or most fremd)

entries.meaning: (rare, chiefly dialectal) Strange, unusual, out of the ordinary; unfamiliar.
examples: Something fremd has been going on here.

entries.meaning: (rare, chiefly dialectal) Not kin, unrelated; foreign.
examples: [...] seeing that they were fremd in heart, if they were kin in blood.

entries.meaning: (rare or dialectal) A stranger; someone who is not a relative; a guest.
